"Roeb M., Neises M., Monnerie N., Sattler C., Pitz-Paal R.","Technologies and trends in solar power and fuels",2011,"Energy and Environmental Science","4","7",,"2503","2511",,,10.1039/c1ee01128f,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-79959814288&partnerID=40&md5=9601e7b70177115bf8ebac8fcc40c496","German Aerospace Center (DLR), Institute of Technical Thermodynamics, Solar Research, 51170 Köln, Germany","Roeb, M., German Aerospace Center (DLR), Institute of Technical Thermodynamics, Solar Research, 51170 Köln, Germany; Neises, M., German Aerospace Center (DLR), Institute of Technical Thermodynamics, Solar Research, 51170 Köln, Germany; Monnerie, N., German Aerospace Center (DLR), Institute of Technical Thermodynamics, Solar Research, 51170 Köln, Germany; Sattler, C., German Aerospace Center (DLR), Institute of Technical Thermodynamics, Solar Research, 51170 Köln, Germany; Pitz-Paal, R., German Aerospace Center (DLR), Institute of Technical Thermodynamics, Solar Research, 51170 Köln, Germany","Solar radiation is the largest indigenous energy resource worldwide. It will gain a significantly more relevant role in covering the energy demand of many countries when national fuel reserves fall short and when demand increases as is expected within the next 10 years. If solar energy is transformed into heat by concentrating and absorbing the radiation, energy can be stored easily. Thermal energy from mirror fields that focus solar radiation not only is able to generate electricity but also can be used to generate storable heat, to desalinate salt water or to synthesise fuels from water and carbon dioxide to store, transport or use them on-site. The application of concentrated solar radiation as a primary energy source can help to decarbonise electricity generation and many other sectors to keep the chance of staying within the 2 °C goal for limiting the effects of global warming. The aim of the present contribution is to give an overview on the state-of-the art of technologies for solar thermal power production and fuel production and to describe the status and outlook of commercial projects and perspectives of market development. © 2011 The Royal Society of Chemistry.",,"Commercial projects; Concentrated solar radiation; Electricity generation; Energy demands; Fuel production; Generate electricity; Market development; Mirror field; Primary energy source; Solar thermal power; State of the art; Status and outlook; Carbon dioxide; Electric generators; Energy management; Energy resources; Fuels; Global warming; Solar radiation; Sun; Solar energy; absorption; carbon dioxide; electricity generation; energy efficiency; energy market; energy resource; global warming; market development; solar power; solar radiation; spatiotemporal analysis",,,,,,"www.DLR.de/tt/med-csp, MED-CSP Concentrating Solar Power for the Mediterranean Regionhttp://www.dii-eumena.com/, Desertec Industrial Initiativewww.DLR.de/tt/aqua-csp, AQUA-CSP Concentrating Solar Power for Seawater DesalinationKiczek, E., (2010) FCH-JU Stakeholder Assembly, , Brussels, Belgium; Sattler, C., Roeb, M., Monnerie, N., Graf, D., Möller, S., (2006) Solar 2006, 8. , Denver, Colorado, USA; http://www.solarpaces.org, IEA Implementing Agreement SolarPACES - Solar Power and Chemical Energy SystemsImage database of DLR Solar ResearchLovegrove, K., Burgess, G., Brunswick, R., Coventry, J., Cumston, J., Pye, J., (2009) Solar PACES 2009, 15. , Berlin, Germany; (2010), http://www.nexteraenergyresources.com/content/where/portfolio/pdf/segs. pdf, Solar Electric Generating Systems(2004), Real Decreto 436/2004(2007), Real Decreto 661/2007(2006), Solucar, PS 10 Final Technical Progress Report: 10 MW Solar Thermal Power Plant for Southern Spainhttp://www.solucar.es/corp/web/es/index.html, Solucar websiteKearney, A.T., Solar Thermal Electricity 2025, , www.atkearney.com/images/global/pdf/STE_2025_Study_Report_June_2010.pdf; Zarza, E., (2002) J. Sol. Energy Eng., 124, pp. 126-133; Submarine Cable